fields: Bone remodeling takes place along {{c1::lines of stress}}
This allows bones to stay stong against the forces they see regularly
The phases of the bone remodeling process are {{c1::resorption by osteoclasts}}, {{c1::creation of new bone by osteoblasts}}, and {{c1::osteoblasts embedding themselves to become osteocytes}}
The average timeline for bone remodeling is {{c1::~200 days}}
The stages of bone remodeling are:

-Localized hemorrhage + clot formation
-Clean up by macrophages
-proliferation of osteoprogenitor cells
-Production of immature bone
-Broken ends united by trabeculae united forming callus
-callus remodeled along stress lines

-Low Ca intake
-Decreased sex steroid levels (especially estrogen)
-Decreased exercise
-Consumption of calcium depleting substances

-Increasing peak bone mass in children
-Regular exercise
-Healthy Ca intake
Hormone replacement therapy (and use of bisphosphonates)
-Avoiding Ca depleting substances
The three types of Muscle are {{c1::smooth}}, {{c1::cardiac}}, and {{c1::skeletal}},
F- Even though calcified cartilage forms as a precursor to bone development, bone is NOT calcified cartilage; <u>cartilage does not become bone, but rather is replaced by bone</u>

Intramembranous bone formation

-{{c1::Mesenchymal}} cells differentiate into osteoprogenitor cells.
In developing bone, the bony spicules {{c1::fuse::separate/fuse}} to form larger pieces of bone tissue
{{c1::immature}} bone which is initially produced is remodeled by osteoclasts and osteoblasts.

Endochondral Bone formation

-a {{c1::hyaline}} cartilage "model" with the general shape of the bone forms from mesenchyme.
-Cells along the outer {{c2::diaphyseal}} surface differentiate into {{c3::osteoblasts}}, and secrete bone matrix forming a {{c1::periosteal bony collar}}.

ENDOCHONDRAL BONE FORMATION
-A {{c1::hyaline}} cartilage “model” with the general shape of the bone forms from {{c1::mesenchyme}}
-Cells along the outer diaphyseal surface differentiate into {{c1::osteoblasts}}, and secrete bone matrix forming a {{c2::periosteal bony collar}}
-The cartilage in the diaphysis begins to {{c2::calcify}} leading to breakdown of the center of the diaphysis
-{{c1::Blood vessels and CT}} invade the calcified cartilage; the marrow cavity begins to form
-Secondary centers of ossification form in the {{c2::epiphyses}}.

ENDOCHONRAL BONE FORMATION
This occurs after the secondary centers of ossification form in the epiphyses.

-A layer of {{c1::hyaline}} cartilage remains between the {{c2::epiphysis}} and the {{c1::diaphysis}};  This cartilage forms the epiphyseal plate
-The region between the epiphyseal disc and the diaphysis is called the {{c1::metaphysis}}; in the metaphysis, calcified cartilage is replaced by {{c1::bone}}
The cartilage forming the epiphyseal disc can be divided into zones beginning at the region {{c1::farthest::closest/farthest}} from the metaphysis
